yarization,” large monuments were erected near small towns commemorating the medieval conquest of the Carpathian Basin—supposedly, the moment when the Hungarian nation was born. This exactingly researched study recounts the troubled history of this plan, which—far from cultivating national pride—provoked resistance and even hostility among provincial Hungarians. Author Bálint Varga thus reframes the narrative of nineteenth-century nationalism, demonstrating the complex relationship between local and national memories.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aGroup identityzHungary. 0aHungariansxEthnic identity. 0aMemorializationxPolitical aspectszHungary. 0aMemorialsxPolitical aspectszHungary. 0aNational characteristics, Hungarian. 0aNationalismzHungaryxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Austria & Hungary.2bisacsh  a19th century nationalism.  ahabsburg hungary.  ahistorical study.  ahistory.  ahostility among provincial hungarians.  ahungary.  aimpose unified national identity.  alocal and national memories.  amassive project of cultural assimilation.  amedieval conquest of carpathian basin.  amoment hungarian nation was born.  aquixotic episodes in magyarization.  aresistance provoking.  astudy of magyarization.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311099822140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781785333149?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781785333149423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781785333149/original  a978-3-11-099822-1  Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPD